nsformation per recent literature\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.75\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.8,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"This represents the classic direct guanylation route (ornithine + cyanamide \u2192 arginine, Schulze and Winterstein 1899; Tsubokura 2014). Both precursors are literature-supported, and cyanamide formation is highly plausible under UV/early Earth surface conditions. Guanylation under prebiotic conditions has not been shown with high yield, though the step is chemically feasible and catalysis by minerals (e.g., montmorillonite) may improve realism. Path is compact, coherent, and environmental transitions are justified.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [ \"rxn_006\" ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify that guanylation step has not been shown with high yield under strictly prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"Consider alternate minerals or early Earth catalysts\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is largely a variant of the main cyanosulfidic/guanylation strategy but omits details of hydrolysis and amination. Steps are plausible and realistic, but yield data for direct guanylation remains lacking. The environmental transitions and use of surface UV chemistry are strong aspects; ensure hydrolysis conditions are included and chemically justified.\